The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation
		 Tuesday, February 17, 2004 				 EC hints at April 20 start
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT New Delhi, Feb. 16: The  Election Commission has said it may hold Lok Sabha elections  between April 20 and May 5.																								The panel hinted at the dates during daylong discussions with state chief secretaries and directors-general of police from 14 states.																								Todays meeting was one of many such talks the commission has had with state officials since last Thursday in order to prepare for the elections.																								Officials from Bengal today asked the panel to take into account that school examinations there would last until April 26. They also urged it to deploy 305 central paramilitary forces, pointing out that there are 1,200 super-sensitive and 9,000 sensitive booths in the state. Bengal faces a threat from the Kamtapur Liberation Organisation in the north and the Peoples War Group in the south.																								The election panel is likely to visit the state soon.																								Officials from the seven northeastern states also met the commission today to discuss security, but would not divulge details.																								Chief election commissioner T.S. Krishnamurthy has said the panel will take account of school examination dates, weather and availability of security forces before deciding on the election schedule.																								During the elections, the panel will have to put in place nine lakh polling stations, make available 50 lakh polling staff and 600,000 electronic voting machines.																								The home ministry will have to sanction extra security forces for sensitive states under threat from insurgency groups and ultra-Left forces. Jammu and Kashmir tops the security requirements.																								The commission will have talks with the home ministry on Thursday after all states have informed it of their security requirements.																								Officials from Jharkhand, Chhattisgarh and Madhya Pradesh which face threats from Naxalite groups said adjoining states must work closely to ensure violence-free elections.																								States will have to work in collaboration with the commission also, K.K. Chakraborty, additional chief secretary from Chhattisgarh, said. The Maoist Communist Centre and Peoples War are active in Jharkhand, Madhya Pradesh and Chhattisgarh.																								Todays meeting discussed how many phases the elections should be held in. Krishnamurthy does not want many stages. The last elections were staggered across five phases; the panel chief wants no more than four this time.
